. We could speed openl3 quite a bit by swapping it out with pysox, resample the audio into a tempfile and load the templfile for further processing.\r\n\r\n```python\r\n\r\nwith tempfile.TemporaryDirectory() as tempdir:\r\n    filename48 = os.path.join(tempdir, os.path.basename(os.path.splitext(file_path)[0]) + \"_48.wav\")Â \r\n    # resample to 48000 Hz\r\n    tfm = sox.Transformer()\r\n    tfm.convert(samplerate= 48000, n_channels=1)\r\n    tfm.build(file_path, filename48)\r\n\r\n    # load the audio file\r\n    sr = 48000\r\n    audio, srload = librosa.load(filename48, sr=None)\r\n    assert srload == sr\r\n```\r\n\r\nNOTE: this example assumes wav input, and would have to be adapted to support various formats (in particular mp3)\r\n","closed_by":null,"reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/marl/openl3/issues/49/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/marl/openl3/issues/49/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null}